<subsection xml:id="subsec-trigonometric-ratios-of-acute-angles">
    <title>Trigonometric ratios of acute angles</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            An <term>acute angle</term> is an angle that measures 
            <em>greater than 0&#176; but less than 90&#176;</em>. In other words, 
            it is an angle that is smaller than a right angle (90&#176;).
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>Examples of Acute Angles</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>30&#176;, 45&#176;, and 60&#176; are common acute angles in trigonometry.</li>
                <li>Any angle between 0&#176; and 90&#176; is considered acute.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Characteristics of Acute Angles</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>They are always found in right-angled triangles.</li>
                <li>The sum of two acute angles in a right-angled triangle is always 90&#176; because the third angle is the right angle (90&#176;).</li>
                <li>They appear in various geometric shapes like triangles, polygons, and real-world structures.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </introduction>

